    "# Matplotlib - heatmap\n",
    "\n",
    "A heatmap is a two-dimensional visualization in which numeric values are represented using colors. The intensity of the color corresponds to the magnitude (value) at a specific point on the grid.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Main applications of heatmaps**\n",
    "\n",
    "1. **Correlation matrices**  \n",
    "   - They allow you to quickly identify strong and weak relationships between variables in a dataset.  \n",
    "   - They facilitate the preliminary selection of features, e.g. in predictive modeling.\n",
    "\n",
    "2. **Spatio-temporal analysis**  \n",
    "   - Visualization of the intensity of events (e.g. sales, network traffic) along the time axis versus categories or zones.  \n",
    "   - It helps to detect seasonal, daily, or weekly patterns.\n",
    "\n",
    "3. **Geographic maps**  \n",
    "   - Presentation of the density of events or values (e.g. illnesses, accidents) across geographic areas.  \n",
    "   - They enable the quick identification of \"hotspots\".\n",
    "\n",
    "4. **User behavior analysis**  \n",
    "   - Tracking clicks, mouse movement, or scrolling on websites/applications.  \n",
    "   - Optimization of the layout of interface elements for usability.\n",
    "\n",
    "5. **Resource and performance monitoring**  \n",
    "   - Visualization of server load, memory usage, or production output in real time.  \n",
    "   - It helps to catch anomalies or overloads.\n",
    "\n",
    "6. **Detecting anomalies and deviations**  \n",
    "   - Identification of unusual readings, e.g. in medical, financial, or network data.  \n",
    "   - Quick indication of areas requiring further analysis.\n"
   ]
